                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1156">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">119.2/3–1449: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopper</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hong Kong</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-03-14T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 14, 1949—2 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 15—3:11 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>91. In cover received today Chiao Mu returned Dept’s message left with him March
                    10, with personal informal signed note dated March 12 to Vice Consul
                        Service<note n="28a" xml:id="d1156fn28a">Richard M. Service.</note>
                    explaining “very sorry that I cannot forward such a message”. Tone of note was
                    friendly.</p>
                <p>Return of message coincides with Peiping action and Consulate assumes text
                    message radioed Communist headquarters.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 91, repeated Nanking 21, AmEmb Canton 7, Shanghai 26, Peiping
                    unnumbered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hopper</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
